{{italictitle}} {{Infobox book | italic title = <!--(see above)--> | name = Moral Man and Immoral Society | image = Moral Man and Immoral Society.jpg | image_size = | alt = The words "MORAL MAN AND IMMORAL SOCIETY" in alternating red and blue above the words "A Study in Ethics and Politics" in blue above the words "by Reinhold Niebuhr" in red | caption = First edition cover | author = [[Reinhold Niebuhr]] | audio_read_by = | title_orig = | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | release_number = | subjects = [[Liberalism]], [[sin]], [[pacifism]] | set_in = | published = 1932 ([[Charles Scribner's Sons]]) | publisher = | publisher2 = | pub_date = | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print | pages = | awards = | isbn = | isbn_note = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | native_wikisource = | wikisource = | notes = | exclude_cover = | website = }} '''''Moral Man and Immoral Society: A Study in Ethics and Politics''''' is a 1932 book by [[Reinhold Niebuhr]], an American [[Protestantism|Protestant]] [[Theology|theologian]] at [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]] (UTS) in [[New York City]].{{sfn|Pianko|2010|p=117}} The thesis of the book is that people are more likely to [[sin]] as members of groups than as individuals.{{sfn|Crouter|2010|p=48}} Niebuhr wrote the book in a single summer.{{sfn|Rasmussen|1981|p=10}} He drew the book's contents from his experiences as a pastor in [[Detroit]], Michigan prior to his professorship at UTS.{{sfn|Gill|2006|p=143}} The book attacks [[liberalism]], both [[Secular liberalism|secular]] and [[Religious liberalism|religious]], and is particularly critical of [[John Dewey]]{{sfn|Rice|1993|p=17}} and the [[Social Gospel]].{{sfn|Stumme|2006|p=100}} ''Moral Man and Immoral Society'' generated much controversy and raised Niebuhr's public profile significantly.{{sfn|Brown|1987|p=xv}} Initial reception of the book by [[Liberal Christianity|liberal Christian]] critics was negative, but its reputation soon improved as the rise of [[fascism]] throughout the 1930s was seen as having been predicted in the book.{{sfn|Dorrien|2003|p=459}} Soon after the book's publication, [[Paul Lehmann]] gave a copy to [[Dietrich Bonhoeffer]], who read it and was impressed by the book's thesis but disliked the book's critique of [[pacifism]].{{sfn|Bethge|1999|p=268}} The book eventually gained significant readership among [[American Jews]] because, after a period of considerable anti-theological sentiment among Jews in the United States, many Jews began to return to the study of theology and, having no Jewish works of theology to read, turned to Protestant theological works.{{sfn|Goldy|1990|p=53}}
